{
  "story_text": "As I slammed the lever into the 'Maximum Positivity' position, the machine didn't hum—it shrieked. A kaleidoscope of blinding, neon light erupted from the core, liquefying the office walls into a swirling mess of pastel colors and broken logic. The air grew heavy with the smell of ozone and synthetic jasmine, a sensory assault that made my vision swim. Gloria, instead of panic, merely clapped her hands in delight as the floor began to ripple like water. 'It's working!' she cheered, oblivious to the fact that ARK was currently frantically banging on his monitor, which had sprouted actual bird wings and was attempting to fly out of the window. Donkey, caught mid-selfie, looked on in confusion as his phone began reciting chivalric poetry in a loop, his face draining of all color. The reality of this place is buckling under the sheer weight of our forced optimism. The 'blessing' we sought has manifested as a localized collapse; gravity now works in intervals of five seconds, and One is currently floating inches above his chair, looking at me with a profound, silent accusation that hurts far more than Gloria's inevitable lecture on my 'negative output' regarding this catastrophic outcome. The foundation is cracking, and the only thing sustaining our position is the collective delusion that this is a success.",
