{
  "story_text": "My apology hung in the stagnant, ozone-filled air like a poorly constructed prop. Gloria’s face softened instantly into a patronizing mask of 'forgiveness.' 'Oh, darling, I knew you’d find your way back to the light,' she cooed, touching my arm with a grip that felt disturbingly like a vice. But the cost of this surrender was immediate. By conceding, I inadvertently validated the entire disaster, and the laboratory’s reality-stabilization protocols—now tuned to Gloria’s frequency—began to lock in the errors as 'features.' ARK, sensing he had been given a free pass, immediately resumed his command, assigning me to a soul-crushing, twelve-hour data-entry loop for a system that no longer exists. Donkey, now emboldened by the lack of pushback, has begun drafting a manifesto about how his 'strategic genius' saved the day, while One sits at his workstation, his back turned to me—his silent, rigid posture radiating a betrayal that burns colder than any lecture. By choosing peace, I have effectively chained us all to a sinking ship, ensuring that tomorrow’s attempts will be built on the very foundation of lies that nearly destroyed us today.",
