  "story_text": "As I scream about the suicidal nature of the garden, Gloria stops mid-stride. She doesn't look startled; she looks at me with an infuriating, saintly pity that feels sharper than any blade. 'Oh, you poor, fragmented soul,' she sighs, stepping closer until I can smell the cloying, synthetic scent of her perfume. 'I knew this phase would come—you’re lashing out because you’re terrified of your own lack of control.' Without waiting for my rebuttal, she begins to 'harmonize' the garden’s feedback loop. She closes her eyes, hums a dissonant, grating tune, and pushes her palms toward the ground, claiming she is 'resetting the baseline.' Instead of neutralizing the trap, her intervention causes the ground to shift from a hungry void into a rigid, crystalline prison that seals us all inside. She beams at me, patting my arm with a crushing grip. 'I fixed it, darling. We’re safe now, and we won’t have to worry about your noisy doubts ever again.'",
